âœ… 1. Preprocessing and Normalization (with sklearn)
python
Copy
Edit
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler

X = [[1, 200], [2, 300], [3, 400], [4, 500]]
scaler = MinMaxScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

print("Normalized X:\n", X_scaled)
âœ… 2. Linear Regression with sklearn
python
Copy
Edit
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

y = [10, 20, 30, 40]
model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X_scaled, y)

print("Coefficients:", model.coef_)
print("Intercept:", model.intercept_)
âœ… 3. Ridge & Lasso Regularization with sklearn
python
Copy
Edit
from sklearn.linear_model import Ridge, Lasso

ridge = Ridge(alpha=0.1)
ridge.fit(X_scaled, y)
print("Ridge Coefficients:", ridge.coef_)

lasso = Lasso(alpha=0.1)
lasso.fit(X_scaled, y)
print("Lasso Coefficients:", lasso.coef_)
âœ… 4. Plotting Loss Curve (using manual gradient descent)
If you implemented gradient descent manually, you can track loss per epoch like this:

python
Copy
Edit
losses = []
for epoch in range(epochs):
    preds = X_b.dot(theta)
    loss = np.mean((preds - y) ** 2)
    losses.append(loss)

    gradients = -2 / len(X_b) * X_b.T.dot(y - preds)
    theta = theta - lr * gradients

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
plt.plot(losses)
plt.title("Loss Curve over Epochs")
plt.xlabel("Epochs")
plt.ylabel("MSE Loss")
plt.show()
